just_use example-source-file.go

# label: EARLY (demonstration sidecar)
# role: show the minimum sidecar shape

A sidecar is a short brief describing a source file. Its
primary audience is future agents (and humans) picking up
this code months later. The minimum bar is that the reader
shouldn't have to open the source to know the module's role,
maturity, and load-bearing quirks.

## Structure (this file demonstrates it)

- First line: `just_use <filename>` — optional shorthand
  saying "this sidecar describes that source."
- Two header comments: `# label:` (WORKHORSE / EARLY / SPIKE
  / INTRICATE / BUGGY / VESTIGIAL) and `# role:` (one-line
  summary).
- Body: free-form, headings welcome. Typical sections:
  what it does, load-bearing invariants, status, deliberate
  non-goals, pointers to related modules.

## Guidance

- Honest labels. If something is SPIKE, say SPIKE. Hiding
  maturity hurts future readers.
- Cite load-bearing behavior (the thing that will bite you
  if you change it without understanding). Leave
  self-explanatory mechanics to the source.
- Pointers matter: link consumers, memories, sibling
  modules. The sidecar is a node in a graph, not a file
  in isolation.

## When to update

Whenever the source's role changes substantively, or when a
new load-bearing invariant emerges, or when a previously-
WORKHORSE module starts decaying. A stale sidecar is worse
than a missing one.
